First of all, I wasn't on the raid last night (had a track meet) but I do have a bit to contribute regarding &quot;mid-lvl&quot; raids. Some of what I'm thinking comes from the Tower of Frozen Shadow bonanza a few nights ago. I could be wrong, but I think some of the frustration I felt during that &quot;raid&quot; parellels what Glia felt last night. Let me explain...<br>
<br>
I introduced the idea of going into the Tower of Frozen Shadow as mostly an experience/maybe a little nice loot exercise for a group of 35-40ish or two. I'd heard that the place was &quot;very good loot/very good experience&quot; so it sounded like a good place for me to make a substantial chink in the hell level while also having a good time. What I was envisioning was 2 mid-lvl experience groups moving through the tower with a few higher level &quot;guides&quot; buffing, healing, occasionally helping if we bight off more than we can chew, and showing us through the pathing of the tower. These guides were to come only out of generosity and if they had nothing to do. <br>
<br>
What that turned into, for better or for worse (from my point of view, for worse) was basically a full-fledged pick-up raid consisting of a.) the 35-40ish crowd, comprising probably 1/3-1/2 of the raid who were there (atleast I assume) for the same type of experience/loot that I was thinking of in the first place... we would have been content to only go up a few floors as long as experience was good and b.) the high-lvl, 45+ contingent, the majority, who saw the first few floors not as a potentially great xp oppertunity for the mid-lvls, but as a pain-in-the-ass farm for keys... they were there primarily for loot on the higher floors, keys, and perhaps a shot at tserrina to top off the night. Like I said, for better or for worse.<br>
<br>
Basically, that night changed from a slightly inflated xp group (as was my original idea) into a kind of chaotic training raid/key farming/occasional rolls on Studen't Homework event that yielded almost no experience (i got 2 blue bubs in 4 hours of fighting) and no loot to the 35-40ish crowd (the ones who this was setup for in the first place). The higher levels were NOT there as guides; they didn't seem to care one bit whether the lowbie groups got exp/loot, and were there for their own purposes (most highlevel casters rolled on the student's homework). Ultimately, the lowbie groups were just tagging along (atleast I was). Again, this would have been fine if it was what was planned, but it was supposed to be something completely different. <br>
<br>
Alright, I'm done complaining... i hope no one takes offense to the TOFS rant; I am not accusing anyone of anything, I just don't think we were all on the same page. I didn't want to screw up the &quot;raid&quot; in progress by complaining, so I decided just wait a little while until I could formulate my thoughts and let it all out. Now, I DO have a couple of ideas on how to help with some of the annoyance/frustration mid-levels may feel on some of these raids.<br>
<br>
First of all, a level range needs to be set for the &quot;main&quot; raiding group. Anyone higher than this becomes one of the guides. The level range should be set with primarily xp in mind. Then as the raid gets going, the mid-level groups should do ALL the fighting (after all it is a mid-level raid). Someone from the guide group can pull if that makes sense (because they know the zone better or whatever) but they should not actually engage their pulls, just let the raiding group take it off. The guide group should basically just buff, heal, debuff, maybe help kill if the mob is well below 50% health, and as an insurance net in case something goes wrong. <br>
<br>
Also, remember that the guides come out of generosity only. All loot from the raid should go to the players who are actually raiding. <br>
<br>
Now, it is fine if there is some boss mob or something that the higher-level players want to hit (in the case of TOFS this would be the top couple floors). That would be a good incentive for the guides to come and help out. But, remember, it is still primarily a mid-level raid and until it gets to the point of this higher level encounter, the people above the raid group parameters need to stay as strictly guides. <br>
<br>
I think if we pay more attention to some of these things, it will make the lower-level raids more fun for everyone. Higher levels that come need to realize that what they are basically doing is a raid-style powerlevel. If this is not the kind of thing that you want, I would suggest that you don't come along. If you want to come to one of these to help out and have a good time then maybe get a shot at a boss mob or something, then bravo to you. <br>
<br>
Hopefully we can make future mid-level raids more successful and fun for everyone present. Thanks for reading.<br>
<br>
